page.text: On behalf of the Tower School, VHB has conducted an evaluation of the school’s current morning drop-off and
afternoon pick-up operations to determine if a proposed new circulation loop would provide adequate capacity to
accommodate the existing traffic demands. This evaluation included traffic counts, vehicle queuing observations, and
an assessment of the capacity of the proposed loop. This information was analyzed to determine if any potential
impacts would be felt within the neighborhood if drop-off/pick-up operations were consolidated to the proposed
loop. The following text summarizes our findings.
West Shore Road is a north-south, two-lane roadway that runs along the frontage of the Tower School. The posted
school zone speed limit within the vicinity of the Tower School is 20 mph. Sidewalks are present along both sides of
the roadway and land use is primarily residential within the vicinity of the Tower School.
Cornell Road is an east-west, two-lane roadway that is bounded by West Shore Drive to the west and Baldwin Road to
the east. The posted school zone speed limit within the vicinity of the Tower School is 20 mph. Sidewalks are present
along both sides of Cornell Road in the vicinity of the Tower School. The roadway runs through the neighborhood
adjacent to the Tower School and land use is primarily residential.
Dartmouth Road is a north-south, two-lane roadway that is bounded by Lafayette Street to the south and dead-ends
just past Colgate Road to the north. There is no posted speed limit within the vicinity of the project area. Sidewalks
are present along both sides of Dartmouth Road. The roadway runs through the neighborhood adjacent to the Tower
School and land use is primarily residential.
West Shore Drive at Cornell Road is a three-way “T” type intersection with Cornell Road intersecting West Shore Drive
from the east. The Cornell Road westbound approach is under STOP control. All approaches provide a single general-
purpose lane. Sidewalks exist on all sides of the intersection and crosswalks are located on the southbound and
westbound approaches. The Tower School is located on the northeast corner of the intersection.
Cornell Road at Dartmouth Road is a four-way intersection with the Dartmouth Road eastbound and westbound
approaches under STOP control. Sidewalks exist on all sides of the intersection and crosswalks are located on the
Cornell Road northbound and southbound approaches. The Tower School is located just north of this intersection.

West Shore Drive at the Site Driveway is a “T” type intersection with the Site Driveway intersecting West Shore Drive
from the east. The Site Driveway westbound approach is under STOP control. Sidewalks exist on both sides of West
Shore Drive. A crosswalk for the Marblehead Rail Trail is provided just north of the Site Driveway.

text.b: Cornell Road at West Shore Road

page.text: During both peak periods, the majority of Cornell Road westbound traffic turned right onto West Shore Drive
(83% in the morning and 78% in the afternoon). It appears that a substantial portion of this is neighborhood
cut-through traffic not necessarily associated with Tower School.
During both peak periods, a significant number of vehicles turned left onto Cornell Road (161 in the morning
and 99 during the afternoon), which is a combination of neighborhood cut-through and Tower School traffic.
In addition to the TMCs, VHB conducted field observations including the Main Entrance, the Cornell Road side
entrance, and the Bell School drop-off on Dartmouth Road and Colgate Road. These observations were conducted
during the Friday morning drop-off from 7:30 AM to 8:30 AM and during the Friday afternoon pick-up from 2:30 PM
to 3:30 PM. Information gathered included typical dwell times, queue lengths, vehicle circulation patterns, pedestrian
circulation patterns, as well as any behaviors that do not follow the standard recommended procedures.
Under normal drop-off/pick-up operations at Tower School, students can be dropped-off and picked-up at two main
locations: (1) the school’s main entrance off of West Shore Road and (2) the side entrance off of Cornell Road.
Morning drop-off activity lasts for approximately 20 minutes from 7:40 to 8:00 AM, during which minimal queueing
occurs at the entrances and impacts to adjacent roadway operations are minor. Tower School staff members are
stationed at each entrance from 7:40 to 7:55 AM to assist drop-off operations. Staff members assist the students out
of their car so the parents can stay in the car, which minimizes dwell times. The typical observed dwell time of each
Friday afternoon pick-up begins at approximately 2:30 PM when vehicles begin to queue at the school’s entrances
until all students are let out at 3:00 PM. School staff accompany the students outside of both entrances at afternoon
dismissal and assist with pick-up operations until all the students have been picked-up. At the main entrance, the
queue extends onto West Shore Drive beginning at approximately 2:50 PM with southbound vehicles blocking
through traffic and northbound vehicles queued past Cornell Road. Once the vehicles reached the main entrance
door it took less than a minute to load the students. However, queues formed at the exit onto West Shore Drive
creating back-ups within the driveway loop. Queues exiting the driveway and pick-up activity at the Main Entrance
was finished by 3:15 PM. At the Cornell Road entrance, the northbound queue along Cornell Road extended past
Dartmouth Road by 2:50 PM. Vehicles were parked on Amherst Road and these parents gather on the eastern side of
Cornell Road next to the school while they wait to pick-up the students. It should be noted that students are not
allowed to cross or walk down Cornell Road without a parent. Once school is dismissed and the vehicle reaches the
Cornell Road entrance door, it takes less than a minute to load the students and leave. Parents and students who
parked on Amherst Road tended to dwell a little longer. However, all pick-up activity at the Cornell Road side entrance

VHB compiled the field observations and vehicle queue data to establish the peak queue lengths during the morning
drop-off and the afternoon pick-up periods. Table 1 summarizes the queuing observations that were conducted at
the main entrance and the Cornell Road entrance.
Queue observations conducted by VHB on Friday December 5, 2014.
As shown in Table 1, the observed peak queue length during the morning drop-off period was 7 vehicles. The
observed peak queue length during the afternoon pick-up period was a total of 74 vehicles (36 on Cornell Road and
38 at the Main Entrance). . It should be noted that the queue data summarized in Table 1 for the Main Entrance
includes all vehicles within the circulation loop, vehicles queued on West Shore Drive in both directions, as well as
vehicles that parked on West Shore Drive between the Main Entrance and the faculty parking lot. It should also be
noted that total queues at the Cornell Road side entrance include vehicles parked on Amherst Road. Generally
speaking, the peak vehicle queues were split relatively evenly between the two areas during the Friday observations.
Anecdotally, vehicle queues during the afternoon pick-up period Monday through Thursday are typically much lighter
given that grades 6-8 (approximately 100 students) are not dismissed until 4:30 PM on those days.

In addition to the specific queue data collected at the Tower School, general queue observations were conducted
along Dartmouth Road and Colgate Road related to the Bell School. Drop-off activity began a little later for Bell
School, at approximately 8:00 AM. Vehicles primarily arrive on Colgate Road and park on either Colgate Road or
Dartmouth Road. Parents typically get out of their cars and walk their children up to the school. During the morning
drop-off period, a peak of five vehicles were parked on these streets. In the afternoon, Bell School lets out at
approximately 2:30 PM. During this time, a peak of 15 vehicles were parked on Dartmouth Road and Colgate Road.
The queues dispersed quickly and most parents drove on Dartmouth Road to Cornell Road.
Tower School is currently developing a plan for the campus that would involve the creation of a new drop-off/pick-up
loop off of Cornell Road. Along the inside of the proposed loop, approximately 30 parking spaces would be provided,
which would primarily serve as overflow or event parking. Currently, Tower School owns seven houses just south of
the school (two on Cornell Road, one on Dartmouth Road, and four on Colgate Road). As part of the plan, five of
these existing houses would be removed to construct the new loop and the two houses on the north side of Colgate
Road would remain. The proposed loop would involve a discontinuance of Colgate Road north of Dartmouth Road
and the creation of a cul-de-sac where Colgate Road intersects Dartmouth Road, which would facilitate drop-off/pick-
up for the Bell School. The existing houses on this section of Colgate Road would access their driveways from the
proposed loop under this plan. A conceptual layout of the proposed plan is provided in the Attachments.
Based on the observed traffic volumes, queue lengths, and approximate duration of the peak drop-off and pick-up
periods, VHB assessed the potential capacity of the proposed loop illustrated on the above-mentioned plan. As
proposed, the loop would provide approximately 575 ft – 600 ft of effective storage around the one-way loop. The
driveway would be wide enough to accommodate two circulation lanes. It is common traffic engineering practice to
use a length of 20 to 25 feet per vehicle when calculating storage capacities, although a length of 25 feet per vehicle is
often overly conservative. Based on observations of queuing at Tower School during afternoon pick-up, vehicle
spacing was closer to 20 feet. To provide a range, the proposed loop could accommodate approximately 25 to 30
vehicles in each lane. This would result in a capacity of approximately 50-60 vehicles within the proposed loop
without spilling onto Cornell Road, depending on the efficiency of the parking maneuvers. VHB feels that the actual
operating capacity would likely be on the lower end of that range given that some efficiency may be lost at the end of
the loop when vehicles exit onto Cornell Road. Even with minor inefficiencies during the pick-up period, the proposed
loop would still be able to accommodate all of the current Cornell Road activity and approximately 50% of the activity
at the main entrance, without queuing onto Cornell Road.
It is difficult to assess exactly how much of the existing activity at the Main Entrance would shift to the proposed loop.
But it is important to note that if 50% of the activity at the Main Entrance shifted to the proposed loop (approximately
19 vehicles), vehicle queues at the Main Entrance could be contained onsite without spilling onto West Shore Drive.
The actual shift will depend on a number of factors including parents’ personal preference, their origin, their
destination, and what is most likely the most important factor, the comparative time it takes to pick up a student at

either location. It is often observed in traffic engineering that in cases where drivers are given two comparable access
points or access routes, they try both options several times before settling into a preferred pattern. This causes what
is considered a “self-balancing” effect based on the delays that drivers experience. There will certainly be a period of
time when queues will fluctuate between the Main Entrance and the proposed loop as parents get used to the new
pattern. But based on the traffic volume data, queuing data, and the field observations, it is evident that when this
pattern normalizes, the proposed loop provides benefits to the neighborhood through the reduction of vehicle
queues on Cornell Road and West Shore Drive. Further, the proposed loop allows drivers to use different routes to
get back to West Shore Drive and points east, which will improve the congestion and delays at the intersection of
Cornell Road at West Short Drive.
VHB has conducted an evaluation of the existing operations at the Tower School as well as the proposed new
circulation loop for drop-off and pick-up operations. The evaluation of existing operations showed significant vehicle
queues during the peak Friday afternoon pick-up period on Cornell Road as well as West Shore Drive. In addition,
vehicles departing the area after student pick-up experience delays turning onto West Shore Drive both from Cornell
Road and the Main Entrance. Based on VHB’s evaluation of the proposed loop, both of these conditions would be
alleviated with the new plan in place. As stated in this memorandum, with a potential capacity of 50-60 vehicles, the
proposed loop could accommodate all of the existing Friday pick-up activity on Cornell Road and approximately 50%
of the activity at the Main Entrance. Based on the data collected by VHB, queuing on West Shore Drive and Cornell
Road would be minimized or potentially eliminated with the new circulation plan in place. It is VHB’s understanding
that the Tower School will continue to work closely with the Town of Marblehead and the surrounding neighborhood
to refine the plan. This plan will provide significant benefits to the surrounding neighborhood and will improve the
efficiency of operations and safety for Tower School and their families.
